41. Conduct timely reconciliation of their records with CRAAF and RPCI, of the Municipal Treasurer, and GSO in order to arrive an accurate balance of the Accountable forms inventory and Expense.

We revised our prior years audit recommendations that management to:

1. 	Direct the Municipal Treasurer to commit on completing his cashbooks and reconcile with the records of the Municipal Accountant;

2. 	Consider the closing of the depository accounts in the Trust Fund for those completed projects;
3. 	Direct the MTO to gather the missing and lacking data of the cashbook with unreconciled balances; and
4. 	Direct the MTO to prepare cashbook for all the depository bank account of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Management observe the following measures:
Stop the practice of procuring Office Supplies through shopping unless the procurement is emergency in nature;
Submit immediately the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories on Accountable Forms, Plates and Stickers and Medical, Dental and Laboratory Supplies Inventory;
Require the GSO that at the beginning of the year, he shall prepare a PR for supplies and materials needed for the quarter based on the approved Annual Procurement Program. Subsequent requisition from stock shall be made by the head of office or department needing the supplies;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain a Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) for each type of supplies; and
Require the GSO or the property custodian to maintain a Stock Card (SC) for each type of supplies to be reconciled with the Accounting Office ledgers.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the following department heads/committee for the compliance with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015:
Municipal Engineer;
Provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects as per Item VII.c.1 of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015.
Municipal Accountant;
Submit the required copies of PPE Local Road Network Ledger Cards (Annex D format) per Item VII a.1 of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015;
Update the yearly required disclosures as needed;
Keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network; and
Prepare a lapsing schedule regularly for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year.; and
Municipal General Services Officer;
Maintain and submit Local Road Inventory and Road Maps; and
Keep a complete Local Road Network Property Cards for all roads and its components and submit the same to the Audit Team (Annex E format) per Item VII b.2 of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015.
We also recommended that the Inventory Committee submit Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network System (RPCLRN) supported with Local Road Network Maps (Annex C format) per Item VI.3 of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015.

We recommended the following to the Management:
Stop the practice of procurement through reimbursement and strictly comply with the procedures under RA 9184;
Stop the practice of granting cash advances to the LDRRMO and other LGU personnel for the payment of registration and maintenance of rescue vehicle;
Stop the practice of charging payment of registration and maintenance of rescue vehicle under the LDRRMF; and
Require the concerned Municipality Officials to study and recommend measures to eliminate, disbursements paid through reimbursement basis to ensure collection of withholding taxes from suppliers.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Municipal Treasurer explain/justify why there were collections from the year 2016 and 2017 and deposited only in the year 2022;
Require the Municipal Treasurer  explain/justify why AF51 with series number 12714367 to 12714400 issued to her on July 2, 2020 were still unused as of August 24, 2023 and present such series to the Office of the Auditor for verification purposes;
Advise all Tellers/Collectors of the Municipality refrain from borrowing accountable forms from one another; and
Require all Tellers/Collectors  prepare the Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms at the end of every month and submit it to the Municipal Treasurer for consolidation purposes.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Secure authority from the SP for the ratification of the unauthorized placement of time deposits. Otherwise, revert the funds to Current Account Deposits;
Direct the City Treasurer and the City Accountant to submit details regarding the date of the initial opening of the HYSA/Time Deposit Accounts and the specific sources of the funds used for these investments;
Terminate the time deposits in SEF and TF amounting to ₱8.000 million and ₱25.000 million respectively, and use/utilize the funds on priority programs as intended pursuant to Section 100 (c) of R.A. No. 7160 or in the purpose/s for which these were granted, to provide benefit on the intended beneficiaries; and
Ensure that subsequent placement of time deposits is in accordance with the above-mentioned laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require the City Engineering Office to submit justification why the project has stagnated and is still not fully implemented more than one year after its supposed completion;
Ensure that detailed engineering design, survey and investigation for the project have been sufficiently undertaken before bidding and award of contract to prevent incurrence of delays in the project completion and contract implementation;
Forfeit the contractor’s performance security considering that the delay in the completion of the works exceeds 10 percent of the specified contract time plus any time extension duly granted;
Require the contractor to immediately pay the estimated liquidated damages, and determine the best course of action to facilitate the immediate completion of the project;
Direct the Project-in-Charge to strictly monitor the status and implementation of infrastructure projects; and
Strictly adhere with the provisions of RA 9184.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require the City Planning and Development Council and Budget Committee to ensure that all identified and prioritized development PPAs funded from the 20 percent DF are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready. Likewise, require the City Engineering Office to expedite its execution to guarantee prompt accomplishment;
Require the City Planning and Development Coordinator, in coordination with the CEO, to closely monitor and evaluate the implementation of the identified and prioritized development PPAs embodied in the LDP and AIP so that any cause of delay would be immediately addressed;
Specific timeline of implementation should be required from the City Planning and Development Council in its planning for the implementation of identified and prioritized development PPAs;
Require the City Planning and Development Council to evaluate the necessity or continued relevance of PPAs which remained unimplemented as of year-end, and ascertain the viability of implementation in the ensuing year; and
Ensure that all savings from completed PPAs are considered for immediate realignment or reversion to the unappropriated surplus of the 20 percent DF for re-appropriation to other PPAs.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require the Local School Board to conscientiously formulate and approve a balanced budget that is compliant with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting;
Request for inputs from DepEd Official/Schools Division Superintendents in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures that are in accord with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund;
Exert all efforts to fully implement the programmed projects for the year and the unfinished projects of prior years; and
Maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives and take appropriate actions such realignment or reprogramming, if necessary.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require Inventory Committee to conduct physical count on 13 PPE accounts totaling ₱488.282 million and submit an updated RPCPPE;
Direct the Accounting and Property Units to reconcile their records to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in the Property Cards (PCs) and the PPELCs within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee;
Direct the Inventory Committee to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for all obsolete or unserviceable PPEs which is to be used for dropping from the books;
Comply with the uniform property identification system and prominently show in the property sticker the PPEs vital information to include: description of the property, model number, serial number, acquisition date/cost, person accountable, space for the validation/signature of the Inventory Committee; and
Require the Acting GSO to prepare and maintain the complete PCs to facilitate the required regular reconciliation of the PPE accounts.

We recommended, and management agreed that the:
Local Chief Executive:
Undertake the required procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability as provided under Paragraph 8 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
Undertake the required disposal procedures of unserviceable PPE as provided under COA Circular No. 92-386 dated October 20, 1992;
Municipal Accountant:
Prepare adjusting journal entries to revert the derecognition of untraceable/unserviceable PPE made in the accounting records to facilitate the reconciliation process and follow the required procedures before derecognizing these assets from the books of accounts;
Prepare and maintain a detailed Lapsing Schedule showing all items under each PPE account with detailed computation of depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation on a per item basis and other relevant information;
Prepare and maintain PPELCs for each PPE item and update the PPELCs as necessary in the course of reconciliation;
Ensure that the total balance of PPELCs/Subsidiary Ledgers (SL) tally with the balances of controlling PPE accounts in the GL; and
Work together with the Property Unit in reconciling the PPELCs/SLs with the PCs maintained by the Property Unit;
General Services Office:
Prepare and maintain PCs for each PPE item and ensure that the PCs are updated by posting all unrecorded acquisition/ receipt, issue/transfer and disposal of PPE, if any;
Collaborate with the Accounting Unit to reconcile the PCs with the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit; and
After completion of the reconciliation process, prepare all the necessary reports such as IIRUP, PTR and other documents and report to support the derecognition of assets from the books of accounts.

We recommended, and the management agreed that the:
Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of physical count of all road networks of the LGU and submit an updated Report on the Physical Count of Road Network System (RPCRNS) duly reconciled with the accounting records;
Municipal Engineer to provide the OMA and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
GSO to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map to be the basis of recording of PPEs under the Road Networks account;
GSO to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components duly reconciled with the accounting records;
OMA to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network duly reconciled with the records from the GSO and Municipal Engineer;
OMA to ensure the accuracy of information reflected in the accounting records such as the Schedule of Road Networks accounts in the NFS, ledgers, and the individual Local Roads Networks Ledger Cards (LRNLC) for roads and road components for every road network; and
OMA, GSO and Municipal Engineer to complete the reconciliation of their records to establish the correct balance of the Road Networks account at the end of CY 2024.

We recommended, and management agreed that the Municipal Accountant to:
Reconcile the schedules of the Land account with the records of the Municipal Treasurer, GSO, and Municipal Assessor provide schedules thereafter;
Transfer the remaining balance of P31,166.36 to Road Network account;
Trace the unidentified balance to the Municipal Assessor, and the Municipal Treasurer and prepare adjusting entries if necessary and provide accurate schedules thereafter;
Comply with the guidelines set forth in the Manual in preparation of the RPLC; and
Maintain and update the Property Card for the Land account.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Require the City Planning and Development Council and Budget Committee to ensure that all identified and prioritized development PPAs funded from the 20 percent DF are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready. Likewise, require the City Engineering Office to expedite its execution to guarantee prompt accomplishment;

Require the City Planning and Development Coordinator, in coordination with the CEO, to closely monitor and evaluate the implementation of the identified and prioritized development PPAs embodied in the LDP and AIP so that any cause of delay would be immediately addressed;

Specific timeline of implementation should be required from the City Planning and Development Council in its planning for the implementation of identified and prioritized development PPAs;

Require the City Planning and Development Council to evaluate the necessity or continued relevance of PPAs which remained unimplemented as of year-end, and ascertain the viability of implementation in the ensuing year; and

Ensure that all savings from completed PPAs are considered for immediate realignment or reversion to the unappropriated surplus of the 20 percent DF for re-appropriation to other PPAs.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the City Assessor to undertake a general revision of real property assessments every three (3) years as stated in Section 219 of R.A No. 7160;

Require the City Treasurer to undertake efficient and effective strategies to improve the collection of RPT;

Direct the City Treasurer to avail of the remedies by administrative action through a levy on real property or by judicial proceedings to enforce payment from the real property owners of RPT delinquencies as provided in Section 256 of R.A. No. 7160; and 

Require the City Accountant to coordinate with the City Treasurer for the reconciliation of the noted discrepancy of ₱31.795 million between the recorded balances of RPT/SET Receivables against the RPT delinquencies and to prepare the necessary adjustments to correct the understatement of the reported RPT/SET Receivables balance as of year-end.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:

Cause the reconciliation of the RPCPPE with the property records and the accounting records, determine the respective costs of those properties to which none have been assigned in the RPCPPE;

Require the City Accountant and City GSO to prepare and maintain the LCs and PCs, respectively, to facilitate the required regular reconciliation of the PPE accounts as required under Sections 119 and 120 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:

Require the Supply Officer to update and reconcile the inventory records and stock cards at month end to ascertain the value or cost of the inventory;

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of drugs and medicines and medical, dental and laboratory supplies semestrally and reconcile its records periodically with the accounting records;

We recommended and the Management agreed to:

Ensure that all identified and prioritized development PPAs funded by 20% DF are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready. Likewise, expedite execution of these to guarantee the prompt accomplishment of the same;

Direct the supplier concerned to immediately deliver the unused construction materials for the ongoing PPAs covered by Notice of Suspension to the GSO for proper accounting, custody, and safekeeping considering that these had been duly paid. Otherwise, refund the amount paid;

Require the City Accountant to transfer the completed PPA from the Construction in Progress account to the appropriate Property, Plant and Equipment account and provide depreciation. Further, require the Project Engineer to submit a written justification why the project was 100% completed when there was no obligated amount or actual disbursement for the labor component.

We recommended that the:

Local Chief Executive

1.	Temporarily relieve the members of the Inventory Committee of all their regular duties to be able to complete the physical inventory of all PPEs of 	the LGU in due time;

The Inventory Committee

2.	Complete the conduct of physical count of PPE based on the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

3.	Prepare and submit the RPCPPE covering all the PPEs of the LGU;

Property Unit/GSO

4.	Prepare and maintain Property Card for each PPE item and ensure that the PCs are updated by posting all unrecorded acquisition/ receipt, issue/transfer and disposal of PPE, if any;

5.	Work together with the Accounting Unit to reconcile the PCs with the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit;

Accounting Unit/Municipal Accountant

6.	Prepare detailed schedules of all classes of PPE and submit together with the financial statements to support the PPE account balances reported therein;

7.	Prepare and maintain a detailed Lapsing Schedule showing all items under each PPE account with detailed computation of depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation on a per item basis and other relevant information;

8.	Prepare and maintain PPELCs for each PPE item and update the PPELCs as necessary in the course of reconciliation;

9.	Ensure that the total balance of PPELCs/SLs tally with the balances of controlling PPE accounts in the General Ledger;

10.	Work together with the Property Unit in reconciling the PPELCs/SLs with the PCs maintained by the Property Unit; and

11.Take up necessary adjusting entries based on the results of the physical count as embodied in the RPCPPE and other reports and the results of the reconciliation process.

We recommended that Management expedite the completion of the physical count and reconciliation of records and direct the:

1.	GSO to prepare and submit the Inventory and IIRUP, based on the RPCPPE, using the prescribed format for all PPE found unserviceable, obsolete and/or no longer needed;

2.	GSO, through its disposal committee, to conduct immediate disposal of all unserviceable properties following the procedures set forth in COA Circular 92-386, to prevent further deterioration and loss of additional income;   

3.	GSO to update the IIRUP after disposal of unserviceable properties and furnish copy to the Municipal Accountant and Audit Team; and

4.	Municipal Accountant to derecognize/ drop from the books of accounts all disposed unserviceable properties after disposal and recognize gain/loss on disposal.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive ensure the compliance of the LGU with the policies and procedures on Local Roads Asset Management System by requiring the:

1.	Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of physical count of all road networks of the LGU and submit the Report on the RPCRNS;

2.	OMA to ensure the accuracy of information reflected in the accounting records such as the Schedule of Road Networks accounts in the NFS, subsidiary ledgers, and the individual LRNLC for roads and road components for every road network;

3.	GSO to update the Report on Local Road Network and LRNPC for every road network; and 

4.	OMA and GSO to properly reconcile accounting records and property records with the result of the physical count reported in the RPCRNS to establish the correct balance of the Road Networks account at year-end.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations that management direct the Municipal Accountant in coordination with the GSO to:
1. 	Examine and review the supporting documents of the outstanding payables and communicate with the creditors/payees for possible payments of the claims if transactions are found valid and regular;

2. 	Confirm and/or request the creditors of the outstanding payables with missing or misplaced supporting documents to submit their evidence of the claim, otherwise, the claim be reverted to the unappropriated surplus.

We recommended that management direct the:
1. 	Municipal Accountant to strictly follow the perpetual inventory method in recording and accounting of inventories held for distribution;
2. 	Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain SLC for each item of inventories held for distribution as the perpetual inventory record;
3. 	Heads of the custodian units of inventories held for distribution, such as the Municipal Health Officer (MHO), Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer (MSWDO) and LDRRMO, to prepare and maintain stock cards and other periodic report to record receipts and issuances/distributions thereof, to monitor all movements and balance of inventories within the year, and submit copies of the said reports to the GSO for consolidation;
4. 	GSO to assist the custodian units on the preparation of stock cards and other periodic reports and consolidate the same periodically for proper monitoring and recording of inventories held for distribution; and   
5. 	Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of inventories at least once a year and prepare and submit the RPCI not later than January 31 of each year.

We recommended that management adopt the following measures:
1. 	Provide timeline for every program/project and make sure that the timelines set are realistic and are strictly followed;
2. 	Fast track the implementation of those PPAs which have not yet been started and have remained unfinished as at year-end;
3. Ensure that approved suspension orders are supported by relevant certifications or supporting documents; 
4. Craft detailed project monitoring and evaluation guidelines not just to ensure accountability and completion of PPAs within the timelines set but also to institutionalize best practices and interventions for infrastructure and non-infrastructure projects;
5. Management stops the practice of charging against the 20 per cent DF the expenditures which do not have direct contribution to the attainment of desirable socio-economic development; 
6. 	Require the Sanggunian concerned that authorization for realignments of funds be made through the passage of an Appropriation Ordinance as prescribed under Sections 321 and 336 of RA 7160, duly submitted to the Sangguniang Panlalawigan for review; 
7. 	Require the Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant to ensure that no disbursements are made from reprogrammed funds unless supported with an Appropriation Ordinance; and
8. Management strictly observes the guidelines provided by the DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-01 in the appropriation and utilization of the 20% EDF.

We recommended management to:

1. 	Discontinue granting Special Cash Advance to elected officials under the Peace and Order Public Safety PPAs;

2. 	Discontinue the direct reimbursement of expenses from cash advance and implement the withholding of taxes for purchases made;

3. 	Direct the Municipal Accountant to check and verify the completeness of 	supporting documents attached to the voucher. Management to provide specific duties and responsibilities of casuals, job orders and contractual employees;

4. Accomplishment reports likewise be submitted by concerned employees before payment of salaries is made;

5. 	Implement PPAs identified in the POPS plan;

6. 	Effect necessary adjustments in the books to reflect the transactions in their appropriate/correct accounts as discussed above; and

7. 	Ensure proper recording and classifying of accounts to fairly present the FS of the LGU to comply with the requirements of IPSAS 1, COA Resolution No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 and P.D. 1445.

We recommended management to:

1. 	Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Property Division/Unit, carefully plan/strategize on how to conduct and complete the physical inventory within the prescribed period and prepare a PIP containing, at the least, the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, the cut-off date and a schedule specifying the dates and location of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory.

2. 	Local Chief Executive thoroughly review and approve the PIP and direct the Head of the Inventory Committee to ensure that the inventory taking activities are executed in accordance with the approved PIP in order to complete the conduct of physical count within the prescribe period;

3. 	Local Chief Executive, through the Inventory Committee, ensure the adoption of a uniform property identification system for PPE and assign a unique property number to each PPE item following the numbering system as provided in Section 5.6 of the circular;

4. 	Local Chief Executive, through the Inventory Committee, ensure that all PPE items are attached with property stickers showing all vital information of the PPE as required under section 5.7 of the circular;

5. 	Property Unit/GSO prepare a List of PPEs Found at Station (Annex B of the Circular) and List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs (Annex C of the Circular) based on the RPCPPE and submit a copy to the Accounting Unit for recording purposes;

6. 	Property Unit/GSO follow the procedures for the disposition of non-existing/missing PPEs provided under Paragraph 7 of the Circular; and

7. 	Accounting Unit/ Municipal Accountant take up the necessary accounting entries to recognize PPEs found at station, recognize the loss of PPE and to set up the corresponding receivables from the concerned accountable officer/ personnel based on the lists submitted by the GSO/Property Unit.

Formulate more realistic socio-economic and environmental programs and projects and prioritize their implementation according to the needs of the constituents to avoid constant reprogramming and reversion;
Focus on those projects and activities proposed or recommended by the members of the Municipal Planning and Development Council that are endemic to their area of jurisdiction that will fit the genuine capability of the Municipality to undertake such projects directed to yield and precise Annual Investment Plan; and
Require the Executive Committee to ensure that the decisions of the council are faithfully carried out and implemented.

We recommended that the Management:

Direct the Municipal Engineer submit the Agency Certificate of Acceptance, Test Result, if any, of the contracts or projects enumerated in Table 1 hereof;

Direct the Contractor deliver the uninstalled materials noted in the Construction of Multi-Purpose Evacuation Center at Matusalem National High School located at Matusalem, Roxas, Isabela, otherwise the amount of P128,243.76 representing the uninstalled materials shall be deducted from the contract cost or to be refunded by the contractor, if already paid;

Undertake the necessary corrective measures/rectification of the deficiencies noted (scaling of concrete pavement/ longitudinal cracks) in the Concreting of Barangay Roads located at Rizal, Lucban and Rang-ayan, Roxas, Isabela and submit pictures taken before, during and after the rectifications made. After which, submit a written request for re-evaluation/inspection thereof together with the Statement of Work Accomplished (SWA) on the rectifications undertaken, otherwise, the corresponding computed value of the deficiencies noted shall be disallowed in audit;

Justify in writing why the installed 2 pcs. solar control panel in the amount of P290,000.00 at Barangay San Jose, Roxas, Isabela were smaller in size as compared to the installed 2 pcs. solar control box at Barangay San Placido, Roxas, Isabela which have the same specifications as programmed; and

Justify why there was a delay in the implementation of the following projects: (1) Construction of Two (2) Storey Multi-Purpose Building with Child Development Center and Barangay Health Station, Vira, Roxas, Isabela; (2) Construction of Silage Bunker located at Sinamar, Roxas, Isabela; and (3) Construction of Multi-Purpose Two (2) Storey Building for Barangay Hall, Day Care Center and Barangay Health Station located at Lucban, Roxas, Isabela, otherwise, a Notice of Disallowance will be issued based on the computed liquidated damages.

We recommended that the Management implement the following measures:

Explain / justify why the progress payment to C.R Domingo Construction & Power Dev’t Inc. for the construction of local access road was paid despite the non-preparation of a duly verified and certified SWA;

Advise the Municipal Accountant not to process payment to contractors of infrastructure projects without the preparation and attachment of duly certified SWA in order to ensure that the total amount claimed and paid corresponds with the actual accomplishments of the projects;

