Municipal Accountant:
Record the transaction based on the nature of expenses not on the accounts stated in the Obligation Request;
Reclassify the affected real accounts, and exercise caution in the recording of transactions to minimize, if not totally eliminate, errors in the recording of transactions;
Ensure that the subsequent expenditures of the Municipality are classified in accordance with the new, records and reports in accordance with the MNGAS;
Adhere with GAAP; and
Reconcile material differences between the FS and GL and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to arrive at the corrected account balances.
Municipal Budget Officer:
Investigate the causes of discrepancies between the GL and SAAOB;
Effect the necessary adjustment;
Exercise diligence in the keeping of accounts in order to render accurate financial reports in ensuring year;
Review the budget for succeeding years covering lump sum appropriations to OMOE accounts and follow the account description mentioned in COA Circular No. 2015-001 dated December 1,2015; and
Revise the budget in accordance with the results of the review.

We recommended that the:
MDRRMO prepared and submit the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on or before 15th day after the end of each month;
MDRRMO ensure that all the  programs/projects for disaster be implemented during the year to ascertain the readiness of the Municipality incase of calamity; and in case there is change in the preciously proposed projects, see to it that the disaster council is guided by DILG,DBM and NDRRMC Joint Circular No. 2013-01 dated March 25,2013 wherein the unexpended  balance of disaster fund may be released and utilized for new expenditure items upon submission of a revised Annual Investment Plan (AIP) as approved by the local Sanggunian and the Local Chief Executive upon  recommendation of the council and in accordance with the approved disaster plan;
Municipal Budget Officer and MDRRMO limit the charging of expenses to those Program, Project and Activities included in each thematic area of DRRM and adhere to the provisions of the regulations in the proper utilization of LDRRMF to strengthen the disaster risk reduction management system of the Municipality; and
Municipal Accountant ensure that disbursement vouchers are supported with the necessary documentary requirements before its approval for payment of claims against government funds and transfer and record the unexpended or unobligated balances in the TF book using the proper account trust Liabilities-Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund.

We recommended and the management agreed that:
The Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant refrain from charging the wages of the Focal Point Person and gasoline on hauling of garbage, fertilizer and regraveling from the LDRRMF; and stop the practice of charging the expenses for programs, projects and activities although related to disaster risk management if not supported with approved specific appropriation for the purpose;
The Municipal Accountant transfers and records the unexpended/unobligated balances of LDRRMF of P2,037,328.96  for the current year and P468.55 of the previous years in the Trust Fund book using the proper account Trust Liability-DRRM; ensure that disbursement vouchers are supported with the necessary documentary requirements before its approval for payment of claims against government funds;

We recommended for the Local Chief Executive to:

Require the submission of original official receipts issued by the ticketing agencies for all travels as per attached schedule within 15 days from receipt hereof; 

Require all municipal officials and employees involved and the ticketing agencies concerned to render justification on the excessive variances accounted per plane ticket;

Obtain ticket directly from the airlines or IATA-accredited travel agencies or consider opening a government account to any major airline companies to avoid similar excessive charges for tickets; and

File appropriate case against erring travel agencies or municipal officials/employees.

Hire only JO personnel in accordance to the necessity and urgency of the department’s needs;

Assess the individual  assignments of all job order personnel to avoid redundant and duplicating work accomplishments; 

Indicate the  nature of work of laborers in the JO Contract; and

Require the JO personnel to submit accomplishment reports for the work/job performed during the pay period duly certified by their immediate supervisor.

Immediately stop the utilization of SEF for purposes other than those provided in the Letter of Instruction No. 1462, series of 1985, implementing guidelines of RA 5447; Sections 100 and 272 of R.A. No. 7160; DECS-DBM-DILG nos. 01, series of 1998, supplemented and clarified per  DECS-DBM-DILG nos. 01-A, series of 2000 and 01-B, series of 2001 and    Section 83 of the Manual on NGAS for Local Government Units, Volume I; 

In case of fund transfers, a MOA between the transferor and transferee should be made; and

Instruct the members of the Local School Board to formulate PPAs in accordance with the above stated provisions of law.

Recommendations:
Require the Inventory Team to facilitate the conduct and submission of physical inventory count and reconcile the report with the records of the Accounting and 
GSO/MT to determine the existence, status/conditions and whereabouts of the assets;
The GSO/MT and Accounting Unit will conduct reconciliation of their respective records in order to establish the existence, status/conditions and whereabouts of the assets;
Advise the inventory team to use property tags during the count to facilitate identification and location of the PPE;
The GSO/MT and Accountant shall have to maintain Property Cards and Equipment Ledger Cards, respectively, to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the property and accounting records;
Provide adequate information on the inventory reports such as the model, serial number, cost, conditions and property number to facilitate identification during the account;
Require clearance from retiring/resigning officials and employees to clear them of their property accountability and cancel the corresponding Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) for the returned items.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the City Assessor to prepare schedule of fair market value for the different classes of real property for enactment by Ordinance of the Sanggunian Panlungsod concerned pursuant to Section 212 of the RA 7160 and Real Property Tax Assessment Roll as of December 31, 2016. Formulate measures to generate reliable information and cause immediate updating  and general revision of assessment and property classification considering that the City is still using the CY 2003 assessment roll;
Direct the City Accountant to set up RPT/SET Receivables at the beginning of the year based on the Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayers’ index cards;
Direct the City Treasurer to avail of the remedies by administrative action to enforce payment on delinquent Real Property Taxes thru levy on real property or by judicial action as provided on Sections 75, 76, and 78 of The New Revisions of the City of Roxas Revenue Code; and
Direct the City Accountant and  Treasurer to justify the basis of recording under JEV No. 10-295-16 (01) dated October 31, 2016 and JEV No. 09-024-16(221) the RPT/ SET receivables valued at ₱42.317 million and             ₱28.211 million, respectively.
The Audit Team issued Audit Observation Memorandum (AOM) No. 2017-001 (2016) dated January 10, 2017 for the foregoing observations and recommendations.

We recommended that Management:
Require the City Engineer to strengthen and hasten the full implementation of PPAs programmed in the CY’s 20% AIP as well as those in the Continuing Appropriation particularly those partaking the nature of Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses, either by administration or contract;
Intensify detailed engineering/planning activities so as not to hamper project implementation and formulate PPAs having detailed description, such as the specific project name, location, timely preparation of Program of Works, feasible schedule of project implementation, expected output, and ready Program of Works, for timely implementation of the project;
Refrain from formulating PPAs which are not among those described by the provisions in the utilization of the 20%DF; and
Review unimplemented PPAs in CY 2016 and ascertain viability of implementation for the ensuing year, otherwise, reprogram for a more viable and significant PPAs in accordance to the socio-economic development and environmental management requirements.
The Audit Team issued Audit Observation Memorandum (AOM) No. 2017-07 (2016) dated January 23, 2017 for the foregoing observations and recommendations.

