We recommended that Management:
Direct the LEE management to review LEEs Business Plan and its operation including management, staffing, risk analysis, marketing and sales pursuant to Section 5.3 of the Manual on the Setting up and Operation of Local Economic Enterprises;
Recommend for the updating of the Revenue Code Ordinance on LEEs, specifically on the rates and unit of measures considering these were not updated since 2010;
Implement stall rates increase corresponding to 50 percent, as provided in the 2010 Revenue Code to augment the operation. Come-up with appropriate control measures that would enhance the  operation of the LEEs, to ensure viability and profitability of the enterprise, that will benefit the general public, thru better operating practices; and
Apply the profits and income derived from the LEEs operation, as provided in Section 5.1 of the Manual on the Setting up and Operation for Local Economic Enterprises.
First, cost of improvement, repair and related expenses of the LEE;
Second, return of advances received by the LEE to the General Fund (GF); and
Any excess shall form part of the GF.
The Audit Team issued Audit Observation Memorandum (AOM) No. 2017-010 (2016) dated February 1, 2017 for the foregoing observations and recommendations.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal General Services Officer shall maintain updated and properly accomplished property cards for property accountabilities;
The Inventory Committee headed by the General Services Officer shall conduct a complete actual physical count of PPE. The result of the physical count shall be reported in RPCPPE in accordance with the above guidelines and are promptly reconciled with accountabilities recorded in the books of accounts and the property cards and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant
Closely monitors the use of CAs by the officials and employees;
Remind the employees concerned to liquidate their CAs within the prescribed period provided in Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Require complete documentation before recording the liquidation of CAs;
Strictly comply with documentary requirements cited COA Circular No.2012-001;
Maintain SL in order to properly monitor the grant and liquidation of CAs;
Reclassify the affected real accounts, and exercise caution in the recording of transactions to minimize , if not totally eliminate, errors in the recording of transactions; and
Strictly record all financial transaction  and operations conformably with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles using the accounts prescribed under the PPSAS.
Concerned Official and Employees to:
Attached the RER for the transportation expenses with no Official receipts; and
Liquidated the CAs granted to them on the prescribed period.

We recommended that the:
Management require the officials and employees liquidate immediately the outstanding CAs as of year-end;
Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to closely monitor the liquidation of CAs as soon as the settlement falls due by issuing Reminder Letters to concerned officials and employees;
Municipal Treasurer withholds any payment due to officers and employees, if they refuse to comply with the demands made by the Accountant regarding the immediate settlement/liquidation of the outstanding CAs; and
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Human Resource Officer ensure that all officers and employees of the Municipal Government be cleared first in all their accountabilities before they be allowed to leave or separate from the service pursuant to existing rules and regulations.

We recommended that the management:
Consider revisiting the pro-forma Market Lease Contracts and effects necessary revisions, if any;
Strictly enforce the  pertinent provisions of the New Revenue Code and likewise incorporate the same in the Lease Contracts relative to the imposition of penalties for the delinquent Stallholders and the adjusted rates that should be imposed as per the Revenue Code and the present occupants be given preference over the stalls upon payment of required fees;
Properly monitor all the Stall Market Contracts to ensure that only Stallholders with valid contracts occupy the market stalls. Otherwise, impose necessary actions as provided for in the Municipality’s Revenue Code;
Municipal officials consider the options in Section 3.4 of the Local Budget Circular No.100 wherein the personnel in the Operation of the Market be transferred to the Plantilla of Personnel under the General Fund due to continuous incurrence of losses;
Management adapts measures on how to increase income which can include intensified implementation of the policies under their present Revenue Code; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare yearly financial statements for the Municipality’s LEEs for proper monitoring of its operations.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that:

The inventory committee should immediately complete the physical inventory count and submit a copy thereof to the Auditor;

The Municipal Treasurer should maintain property cards for PPEs with complete information. These property cards should be reconciled with other property records like Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE);

The Municipal Accountant should ensure that property subsidiary ledgers contain complete details/description of the PPEs to facilitate proper reconciliation with the inventory report of the inventory committee. Moreover, the Municipal Accountant should ensure that monthly depreciation is recognized in the books so that the cost of all the PPEs are allocated over the estimated useful life of the assets; and

In case of loss of property, the officer immediately accountable thereof should file an application for relief from accountability. The request should be accompanied by the following documents (Sec. 151 of COA Circular No. 92-386):

Notice of loss showing the exact date of filing and receipt in the office of the auditor concerned or the COA;

Affidavit of the accountable officer containing a statement of facts and circumstances of the loss;

Affidavits of two (2) disinterested persons cognizant of the facts and circumstances of the loss;

Final investigation report of the office or department head and proper government investigating agency on the facts and circumstances surrounding the loss;

A list and description including book value, date of acquisition, property number, account classification, condition of the property, and other additional relevant information on the properties lost duly certified by the GSO, or municipal treasurer, as the case may be;

Comment and/or recommendation of the LCE on the request;

Exact or accurate amount of government cash or book value of the property, subject of the request for relief;

Memorandum Receipt/ARE, if any, covering the properties subject of the request; and

In case of delay in filing of notice, satisfactory explanation or the reasons for such delay.

Require immediate liquidation by concerned officials/employees of previous year’s unsettled cash advances totaling ₱4,158,516.99 and ₱157,672.35 representing those unsettled cash advances by personnel/employees who are no longer connected with the Roxas City Government including personnel of National Government Agencies  who are no longer assigned with the City; 

Require immediate and full liquidation of cash advances granted in CY 2015 by issuing demand letters to those concerned;  

Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees with unsettled accounts. Unsettled cash advances should be deducted from the salaries of those concerned;

Demand immediate settlement of cash advances granted to personnel of National Government Agencies assigned in the City including those personnel planning to retire/resign; and

Henceforth, strictly comply with COA Circular 97-002 dated                February 10, 1997 and Section 14 of E.O. 298 dated March 23, 2004 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances and Item 6.0 of COA Cir. 2012-004 dated Nov. 28, 2012 on the Demand for Immediate Liquidation and Settlement of All Cash Advances Outstanding as of December 31, 2011. In particular, send demand letter to those no longer connected with the City Government, otherwise, institute appropriate action against them.

Require the COs to prepare and submit the monthly RAAF to the CT; 

Require the CT to prepare and submit monthly the CRAAF to the COA Audit Team on or before the 5th day of the following month;  

Conduct regular physical count of all accountable forms and reconcile with the monthly consolidated CRAAF; and

Henceforth, strictly comply with Sections 50 and 51 of the Manual on the NGAS, Volume II for LGUs, Volume II.
